                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d321">
                <head>No. 321.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Nelson</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Fish</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1872-06-07">
                            <hi rend="italic">June</hi> 7, 1872</date>. (Received June
                        28.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 582.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The only military events I have to record since
                    my last general dispatch are the capture of Monterey, on the 31st ultimo, and
                    the defeat of the rebel generals Guerra and Marquez, near the city of Durango,
                    about the same date. Both events are as yet known only by brief telegraphic
                    dispatches, but it seems that the capture of Monterey was preceded by a
                    hard-fought battle, in which a portion of the army of General Corella was
                    routed, and that nothing is certainly known of the whereabouts of that
                    general.</p>
                <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>THOMAS H. NELSON.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
